[[File:Led wall washer.jpg|thumb|LED wallwasher 24 W]]
'''Wallwashing''' is a popular name for a [[lighting design|lighting design technique]] for illumination of large surfaces. It is mainly used with [[contemporary architecture]]; in public cultural buildings, museums and galleries; and in [[landscape lighting]]. 

Most of what one actually sees, entering a room, are the vertical surfaces. The illumination requires [[asymmetry|asymmetric]] lighting fixtures, which, in a number of 3 or more in a line, can produce evenly illuminated walls. It is a tool mainly used by [[lighting designer]]s, to create lighter spaces or making the rooms seem brighter or higher. The technique is similar to the "horizon" technique used in [[theatre lighting]].<ref>https://www.alconlighting.com/blog/lighting-design/what-are-architectural-lighting-fixtures/</ref>

